One America, Two Nations
New York — As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting votes in the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the results are finalized, recounts and legal challenges will certainly follow.
This is expected in this highly competitive, record-breaking election.
Only U.S. citizens can vote in the presidential election, but this choice affects people all over the country.
If it is too early to determine the election results now, it is not too early to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country.
On the positive side, the United States remains a strong democracy.
Despite practical restrictions related to the pandemic, voter participation remained high.
The process seems to be proceeding as planned.
And there have been few incidents of violence.
Courts are investigating decisions by the U.S. Postal Service that appear to be politically motivated and have hindered the delivery of ballots from regions where votes are expected to mainly come from the Democratic Party.
Current U.S. President Trump's baseless claim of victory on Tuesday evening received little response, and his demand to stop the counting of votes (at least in the states where he was leading) seems to have been ignored.
However, it is concerning that the division among U.S. voters remains significant.
The votes for the two candidates are almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a divided government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The governor and state legislative seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republicans having a slight advantage).
The anticipated "blue wave" for the Democratic Party did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, winning about four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million.
However, Republicans held onto many seats that were predicted to flip, while the Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result did not come from strong authorization, nor did it stem from political maneuvering.
Trump's poll numbers were very good, he received 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter in U.S. presidential election history, surpassing any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily新增 cases of COVID-19, with over 100,000 new cases and more than 1,000 deaths each day.
Just as the consequences of his government's mishandling of the pandemic were becoming most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump lost, which seems likely, he will still hold significant influence, especially if he remains in the public spotlight (which also seems possible).
Even though he himself is not running, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee in the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican Party will be far from the party of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern form of American populism — will still remain a powerful force.
It is no surprise that, despite having no evidence, Trump strives to portray himself as noble and upright, and attempts to undermine the legitimacy of the election results, accusing them of fraud.
Many of his supporters will reject the legitimacy of Biden's presidency.
Trump is very likely to never concede, and even less likely to attend the inauguration ceremony of his successor.
As Will Rogers put it, Trump has never encountered a rule he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorize themselves into different communities and regions based on shared views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national civic curriculum has facilitated the segmentation of people across different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that the country's segmentation is mostly not along economic lines.
People from all social classes voted for both candidates, and voting patterns by demographics, gender, and race were not as one-sided as many predicted.
Their differences mainly lie in the remedies.
Education level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographic location. Republican voters tend to live in suburbs and rural areas, while Democrats tend to live in metropolitan areas.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy does not seem to be very important in campaigns, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Against this backdrop, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms in the way the president is elected or how the government operates.
This situation is similar to the reform of the UN Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some people while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who would lose out from change resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This largely depends on the judgment of Republican Senate leader Mitch McConnell, as well as his ability and willingness to cooperate with the incoming President Biden.
Cooperation will also require compromises from Biden, which will certainly be resisted by ideologically minded members of his own party.
Democrats have tried to sharply reject Trump and everything he represents.
But they were not successful.
The Republicans were seeking an election that would validate Trump.
But this also did not go as they wished.
Instead, the election revealed a nation and two distinct groups of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
